{"detail":{"ID":1146,"post_author":"1","post_date":"2017-04-05 23:41:39","post_date_gmt":"2017-04-05 23:41:39","post_content":"The <em>Beijing Line Tower<\/em> is made of a beam of light, round stainless steel mirrors and a wood frame. The tower measures approximately 10 meters high and 6 meters in diameter. By night, a line of light bounces between stainless steel mirrors tracing against the dark sky a 3-dimensional drawing of green fluorescent glow. This drawing can be changed and perfected by climbing on the stairs and adjusting the mirrors. Its form, defined by the straightness of the green laser light beam and the angle it forms at each mirror, can be contained but not fully controlled. The tower is an attempt to free drawing, free it from paper, canvas, and the interior of rooms, to take drawing outside and use it to bamboozle the eye with apparent complexity, then propel it up to the sky to a faint demise of atmospheric dissolution. The Beijing Line Tower's ancestry\u2014the photographs of shadows by Alexander Rodchenko, the luminous theatrical costumes of Oskar Schlemmer, Sol Le Witt's wall drawings, Fred Sandback's string drawings, Lebbeus Woods' installations\u2014can be traced down the annals of a fascination for freedom, freedom of the line from its paper support that is. During the day, the mirrors shine in the sunlight occasionally projecting a glimpse of the passing star moving in the sky.","post_title":"<p>Beijing Line Tower, Siracusa, IT 2014<\/p>","post_excerpt":"","post_status":"publish","comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","post_password":"","post_name":"beijing-line-tower-siracusa-it-2014","to_ping":"","pinged":"","post_modified":"2017-05-15 16:13:02","post_modified_gmt":"2017-05-15 16:13:02","post_content_filtered":"","post_parent":0,"guid":"http:\/\/obra.neptuno.digital\/?post_type=projects&#038;p=1146","menu_order":0,"post_type":"projects","post_mime_type":"","comment_count":"0","filter":"raw","ancestors":[],"page_template":"","po